More pricing power than California

Increases in points affect wines from the different regions differently.

  • For Burgundy, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 22.47% increase in price.
  • For California, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 8.62% increase in price.
  • For Oregon, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 10.35% increase in price.

Pricing power by flavor

  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of fruit, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 10.03% increase in price.
  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of chocolate, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 11.52% increase in price.
  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of tart, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 9.25% increase in price.

Pricing power by type of berry

  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of cherry, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 11.45% increase in price.
  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of blackberry, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 11.75% increase in price.
  • For Oregon Pinots with notes of strawberry, a 1 point ratings increase leads to a 10.4% increase in price.

Summary

Oregon Pinot Noir

  1. Is fruit forward, with hints of chocolate and berries
  2. Has lower overall variance in quality
  3. Has been rising in quality over time
  4. Has more pricing power than California
  5. Is the best bang for your buck

Recommendations:

  1. Work to retain and grow status of Willamette Valley globally
  2. Smaller wineries can overcome status/recognition with targeted flavor profiles
